, England":"Pitminster, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England"},"en":{"1410–1479":"1410–1479","1458–Male":"1458–Deceased","1380–Male":"1380–Deceased","1384–Female":"1384–Deceased","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1384":"1384","1380":"1380","about 1450":"about 1450","Spalding, South Holland district, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Spalding, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Pitminster, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Pitminster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Otterford, Somerset West and Taunton district, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Otterford, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Pitminster, Somerset, England":"Pitminster, Somerset, England","Taunton, Somerset, England":"Taunton, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Treat","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Tritt   or   Trede  .","English: variant of   Threatt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tritt","meanings":["German: apparently from Old High German <i>tretan</i> ‘to step’. However, a South German family of this name are descendants of late 16th-century immigrants from Como, Italy, who bore the name <i>de Triddi</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard Treat was born in 1410, in Pitminster, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Treat, was 30 and his mother, Mrs. John Treat, was 27. He married Joan Buller about 1450. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1479, in Spalding, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1410–1479":"1410–1479","1458–Male":"1458–Surnud","1380–Male":"1380–Surnud","1384–Female":"1384–Surnud","1458":"1458","1479":"1479","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1384":"1384","1380":"1380","about 1450":"umbes 1450","Spalding, South Holland distri